The accession of the '''Serbian monarch''' was legitimized by '''[[coronation]] ceremony'''. The coronation was carried out by church officials.

==Ceremony==
===Middle Ages===
The ritual of crowning a new ruler (royal [[enthronement]]) is attested in the 12th century.{{sfn|Veselinović|Ljušić|2008|p=17}} The coronation of Serbian monarchs took place in the most prominent of churches in the country.{{sfn|Kalić|1998}} The coronation of the Grand Princes of Serbia was likely held at the [[Church of the Holy Apostles Peter and Paul, Ras|church in Ras]].{{sfn|Veselinović|Ljušić|2008|p=17}} The successors of Stefan Nemanja adopted Byzantine ideas on [[Autokrator|self-rule]] and acts on the ruler's [[Anointing|anointment]] and coronation.{{sfn|Veselinović|Ljušić|2008|p=13}} The church official (archbishop, patriarch) anointed and crowned the ruler in the same ceremony.{{sfn|Veselinović|Ljušić|2008|p=13}} Through the [[archiereus]], with the act of crowning, God's grace transits to the ruler.{{sfn|Kalić|1998}}

==History==
===Middle Ages===
The ritual of crowning a new ruler is attested in the 12th century.{{sfn|Veselinović|Ljušić|2008|p=17}} The coronation of Serbian monarchs took place in the most prominent of churches in the country.{{sfn|Kalić|1998}} [[Stefan the First-Crowned|Stefan]] (r. 1196–1228), the son of Grand Prince [[Stefan Nemanja]], was crowned with a crown sent by Pope [[Honorius III]] in 1217.{{sfn|Kalić|1998}}{{sfn|Ćirković|Mihaljčić|1999|p=336}} According to [[Fine Jr.]], he was crowned by a papal legate.{{sfn|Fine|1994|p=107}} It is unknown where the coronation took place.{{sfn|Kalić|1998|p=77}} [[J. Kalić]] believes that it was [[Peter's Church, Ras]].{{sfn|Kalić|1998|p=84}} It has been assumed that Stefan was crowned a second time by Archbishop [[Saint Sava|Sava]], his brother.{{sfn|Marjanović-Dušanić|Ćirković|1994|p=126}} In the second charter to the [[Žiča]] monastery dated to ca. 1224, King Stefan ordered for all future kings to be crowned at that monastery.{{sfn|Kalić|1998|p=77}} His contemporaries and successors called him "the First-Crowned King".{{sfn|Ćirković|Mihaljčić|1999|p=322}}

===Modern===
[[File:The_Coronation_of_the_King_of_Servia_at_Belgrade,_ILN_1904.jpg|thumb|"The Coronation of the King of Servia at Belgrade", ''The Illustrated London News'' (15 October 1904).]]
[[Serbia]]'s last and only modern coronation was in 1904, when King [[Peter I Karađorđević|Peter I]] was crowned in an [[Eastern Orthodox Christian]] ceremony at the Cathedral of the Host of Holy Archangels in [[Belgrade]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtholyoke.edu/acad/intrel/boshtml/bos73.htm |title=The Serbian Revolution of 1903 |publisher=Mtholyoke.edu |date= |accessdate=2008-10-12}}</ref><ref>[http://www.tboyle.net/Royalty/Serbia_Coronation.html The Coronation of King Peter I of Serbia]. Retrieved 2009-10-28.</ref> Serbia became a part of the state of [[Yugoslavia]] after World War I, but Peter did not hold a second coronation and neither of his two successors, the Yugoslav monarchs [[Alexander I of Yugoslavia|Alexander]] and [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|Peter II]], were crowned. This was due to the religious diversity of the new state.

==Regalia==
{{main|Regalia of Serbia}}

===Middle Ages===
Stefan's crown was called "the holy wreath" (''sveti venac'') by Domentijan.{{sfn|Ćirković|Mihaljčić|1999|p=336}} Later, it was called "the god-gifted wreath of the Serbian kingdom" (''bogodarovani venac kraljevstva srpskog'').{{sfn|Ćirković|Mihaljčić|1999|p=336}}

===Modern===

Modern Serbian regalia were created in Paris by the famous Falise brothers jewellers in 1904 for coronation of king Peter I Karađorđević,  and consisted of a [[royal crown]], [[Globus cruciger|orb]], [[sceptre]], [[Mantle (royal garment)|mantle]], and mantle [[buckle]]. The crown, known as the "[[Karađorđević]] Crown", was partially made out of a cannon that [[Karađorđe]] had used during the [[First Serbian Uprising]], and was adorned with details such as the [[Serbian eagle]] and [[Serbian cross]]. The crown, scepter, and orb were decorated with gemstones extracted in Serbia and enameled in the [[Serbian national colours]] (red, blue, and white). The mantle was made out of [[purple]] [[velvet]], embroidered with gold and lined with [[ermine]] fur.

==Symbolism==
 [[File:Coronation of Emperor Dušan, in "The Slavonic Epic" (1926).jpg|thumb|''The Coronation of the Serbian Tsar Stefan Dušan as East Roman Emperor'', part of the ''[[Slav Epic]]'' series by [[Alfons Mucha]], 1926.]]
The sacredness of the Serbian throne is frequently stressed in medieval sources.{{sfn|Marjanović-Dušanić|Ćirković|1994|p=26}} Apart from the throne, the crown was one of the most important royal insignia in the Middle Ages.{{sfn|Veselinović|Ljušić|2008|p=17}}

