'''Robert Michael Snyder''' (born May 4, 1954<ref>[http://www.fcgov.com/police/most-wanted.php fcgov.com] Accessed 2010-01-29.</ref>) is an [[United States|American]] [[author]]. He is best known for authoring the ''Chess For Juniors'' children's book series. He has published multiple books and games, including ''Chess for Everyone'' and ''Unbeatable Chess Lessons''.<ref name="Fugitive Chess Teacher Is Reportedly Caught">{{cite news|url=http://gambit.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/12/05/fugitive-chess-teacher-is-reportedly-caught/#more-2025|title=Fugitive Chess Teacher Is Reportedly Caught|last=LOEB MCCLAIN|first=DYLAN |date=December 5, 2009|publisher=The New York Times Chess Blog|accessdate=30 January 2010}}</ref> He founded the Chess for Juniors club, claiming it was the largest of its kind in the country, and that he trained 36 national chess champions, and holds a world record for having introduced chess to more than 170,000 students.<ref name="Chairman of the Board; Chess Champ Finds Niche Sharing Mastery of Game With Young Enthusiasts">{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/12454398.html?dids=12454398:12454398&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:FT&type=current&date=Jun+09%2C+1997&author=RUSS+LOAR&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Chairman+of+the+Board%3B+Chess+Champ+Finds+Niche+Sharing+Mastery+of+Game+With+Young+Enthusiasts&pqatl=google|title=Chairman of the Board; Chess Champ Finds Niche Sharing Mastery of Game With Young Enthusiasts|last=LOAR|first=RUSS|date=Jun 9, 1997|publisher=LA Times|accessdate=30 January 2010}}</ref> He is considered to be a national and world-renowned master chess player with wins both in the US and international tournaments.<ref name="Fort Collins chess master, advocate has all the right moves Snyder will conduct workshop in Springs ">{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-2762101.html|title=Fort Collins chess master, advocate has all the right moves Snyder will conduct workshop in Springs |last=McGRAW |first=CAROL |date=October 19, 2004|publisher=The Gazette|accessdate=7 February 2010}}</ref><ref name="With Help, He's Making a Move on a World Title; Chess: U.S. champion Harry Akopyan gets the chance, thanks to his Huntington Beach club and an Irvine sponsor.">{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/21571097.html?dids=21571097:21571097&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+15%2C+1995&author=RENEE+TAWA&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&desc=With+Help%2C+He%27s+Making+a+Move+on+a+World+Title%3B+Chess%3A+U.S.+champion+Harry+Akopyan+gets+the+chance%2C+thanks+to+his+Huntington+Beach+club+and+an+Irvine+sponsor.&pqatl=google|title=With Help, He's Making a Move on a World Title; Chess: U.S. champion Harry Akopyan gets the chance, thanks to his Huntington Beach club and an Irvine sponsor.|last=TAWA|first=RENEE |date=Oct 15, 1995|publisher=LA Times|accessdate=30 January 2010}}</ref><ref name="He's Beginning His Own Search for Bobby Fischer">{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/59290327.html?dids=59290327:59290327&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jan+20%2C+1994&author=SUSAN+PATERNO&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&desc=He%27s+Beginning+His+Own+Search+for+Bobby+Fischer&pqatl=google|title=He's Beginning His Own Search for Bobby Fischer|last=SUSAN|first=PATERNO|date=Jan 20, 1994|publisher=LA Times|accessdate=30 January 2010}}</ref> Several of his students have excelled under his tutelage, with results including contention for world and US national chess titles.<ref name="Boy, 11, Moves to Record Book">{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/59786513.html?dids=59786513:59786513&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+09%2C+1988&author=A.+DAHLEEN+GLANTON&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&desc=Boy%2C+11%2C+Moves+to+Record+Book&pqatl=google|title=Boy, 11, Moves to Record Book|last=DAHLEEN GLANTON|first=A. |date=Apr 9, 1988|publisher=LA Times|accessdate=30 January 2010}}</ref>
Snyder has an [[Elo rating]] of 2306 with the [[United States Chess Federation]], but has not played in tournaments since 1990.<ref>[http://main.uschess.org/component/option,com_wrapper/Itemid,181/ Player/Rating Lookup].</ref>
==Personal life== Snyder has been arrested and convicted for multiple sexual assaults involving children dating back to 1983.<ref name="Police: More Victims Possible In Chess Master Case">{{cite news|url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/4978198/detail.html|title=Police: More Victims Possible In Chess Master Case|date=September 15, 2005|publisher=ABC Denver News|accessdate=30 January 2010}}</ref> He was featured on [[America's Most Wanted]] after fleeing [[Colorado]] while still on supervised probation in 2008.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/12/18/robert-michael-snyder-sex_n_397228.html Huffington Post.] Accessed 2010-01-29.</ref> He was found in [[Belize]], and on March 30, 2010 after pleading guilty, was given an open (up to life) sentence.<ref name="Chess master sentenced for sex assault of children">{{cite news|url=http://www.denverpost.com/crime/ci_14786670?|title=Chess master sentenced for sex assault of children|date=March 30, 2010|publisher=The Denver Post|accessdate=30 March 2010|first=Monte|last=Whaley}}</ref>
